`crates/ctx-scan/tests/` is the black-box behavioral contract for
`ctx-scan`: it pins the observable semantics of staleness detection,
`.ctxignore` seeding, scope gating, and the Stop-hook's report-only
guarantee, using real filesystem fixtures and in-memory fakes rather than
unit tests inside the crate. Anyone changing `walker.rs`, `hash.rs`,
`runner.rs`, or `cli::stop_hook` should treat these two files as the spec
to satisfy, not an afterthought to patch.

Both files independently stand up isolated tmpdir fixtures keyed by a
per-test label under `std::env::temp_dir()`, manually removed and
recreated rather than using `tempfile` — neither is safe against a
crashed prior run leaving a same-labeled directory behind, and both
resolve real prompt files via `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR` so tests don't depend
on invocation cwd. Both also import fake/stub `Agent` implementations
from `ctx_summarize::agent` (`RecordingAgent` in scan.rs asserts call
counts and call content; `StubAgent` in stop_hook.rs only seeds freshness
and ignores call counts) — a change to the `Agent` trait signature
requires updating both.

The two files split the contract cleanly: `scan.rs` covers the
regeneration engine (`walk_dir`, `hash`, `check_run`, `update_run`,
`runner::summarize`) including the exact stale-propagation and
scope-gating rules, while `stop_hook.rs` covers only the CLI's read-only
entry point built on top of that engine, and both key off the same
`runner::MAX_TARGETS` constant to test scope-gating/backlog-hint behavior
at the same threshold — a change to that constant's semantics (not just
its value) must be re-validated in both files.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory to check divergence against.